WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:01.084
Having Claude Code

00:00:01.084 --> 00:00:01.793
and being able to use

00:00:01.793 --> 00:00:03.211
Claude Code in my work,

00:00:03.211 --> 00:00:04.004
it almost feels like having this

00:00:04.004 --> 00:00:06.381
super power and this ability to

00:00:06.381 --> 00:00:08.258
send off a sidekick to go

00:00:08.258 --> 00:00:08.967
take the time,

00:00:08.967 --> 00:00:09.634
go figure it out,

00:00:09.634 --> 00:00:10.719
come back, report back.

00:00:10.885 --> 00:00:12.095
One of the reactions I get

00:00:12.095 --> 00:00:13.179
very often is 

00:00:13.179 --> 00:00:13.638
“Holy snap,

00:00:13.638 --> 00:00:14.806
you’re living in the future.”

00:00:20.020 --> 00:00:21.354
When I first joined Anthropic

00:00:21.354 --> 00:00:22.647
I joined a team

00:00:22.647 --> 00:00:24.065
that was working on

00:00:24.065 --> 00:00:24.858
code execution

00:00:24.858 --> 00:00:26.276
and file generation

00:00:26.276 --> 00:00:27.652
within Claude.ai.

00:00:27.652 --> 00:00:28.695
So this is essentially

00:00:28.695 --> 00:00:29.904
giving Claude a computer

00:00:29.904 --> 00:00:30.905
and the ability to

00:00:30.905 --> 00:00:31.906
generate files,

00:00:31.906 --> 00:00:34.200
which include Excel files.

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:35.952
And we had a deadline.

00:00:35.952 --> 00:00:36.828
We were trying to get this out

00:00:36.828 --> 00:00:37.746
in a month and a half.

00:00:38.204 --> 00:00:39.789
I was able to use Claude Code

00:00:39.789 --> 00:00:40.957
to get my groundings

00:00:40.957 --> 00:00:41.750
in the codebase.

00:00:41.750 --> 00:00:42.792
I am primarily

00:00:42.792 --> 00:00:44.210
a backend engineer.

00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:45.336
This is a front end.

00:00:45.336 --> 00:00:46.046
In times past,

00:00:46.046 --> 00:00:47.255
it would take me a long time

00:00:47.255 --> 00:00:47.756
to onboard

00:00:47.756 --> 00:00:48.548
onto the codebase.

00:00:48.548 --> 00:00:49.424
One of the coolest things

00:00:49.424 --> 00:00:51.051
about Claude Code so far

00:00:51.051 --> 00:00:51.801
in my work

00:00:51.801 --> 00:00:52.886
was when I realized

00:00:52.886 --> 00:00:53.803
I could

00:00:53.803 --> 00:00:54.846
hook it up to the

00:00:54.846 --> 00:00:56.014
Playwright MCP.

00:00:56.723 --> 00:00:57.515
Let me show you how I implemented

00:00:57.515 --> 00:00:59.142
the Excel rendering feature

00:00:59.142 --> 00:01:00.226
using Claude Code.

00:01:00.226 --> 00:01:01.728
Firstly, entering my prompt,

00:01:01.728 --> 00:01:02.854
I need you to implement

00:01:02.854 --> 00:01:04.481
the Excel renderer feature

00:01:04.481 --> 00:01:05.982
for Claude.ai.

00:01:05.982 --> 00:01:08.943
Read the EXCEL_RENDERER_DESIGN.md,

00:01:08.943 --> 00:01:10.695
which is the design doc

00:01:10.695 --> 00:01:12.072
that contains a spec.

00:01:12.363 --> 00:01:14.616
Use the Playwright MCP.

00:01:15.158 --> 00:01:16.117
The feature

00:01:16.117 --> 00:01:17.660
should allow a user

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:18.828
to preview Excel,

00:01:18.828 --> 00:01:21.331
CSV, and TSV files.

00:01:21.331 --> 00:01:22.415
So now Claude Code

00:01:22.415 --> 00:01:24.626
is reading the codebase,

00:01:24.626 --> 00:01:27.170
starting the Claude.ai app

00:01:27.170 --> 00:01:28.963
using the Playwright MCP,

00:01:28.963 --> 00:01:30.465
and you can see here

00:01:30.465 --> 00:01:31.633
it does this

00:01:31.633 --> 00:01:32.967
to get an

00:01:32.967 --> 00:01:34.928
accurate read of

00:01:34.928 --> 00:01:36.888
what the feature looks like

00:01:36.888 --> 00:01:37.597
without it

00:01:37.597 --> 00:01:38.681
being implemented yet.

00:01:38.681 --> 00:01:39.432
And now I can see

00:01:39.432 --> 00:01:40.391
the preview.

00:01:40.391 --> 00:01:42.310
It’s not actually implemented,

00:01:42.310 --> 00:01:43.978
and now that it’s ready

00:01:43.978 --> 00:01:44.646
to actually start

00:01:44.646 --> 00:01:45.855
implementing code,

00:01:45.855 --> 00:01:47.273
it asks me for permission

00:01:47.273 --> 00:01:47.982
to make changes

00:01:47.982 --> 00:01:49.067
to those files.

00:01:49.067 --> 00:01:51.111
I will accept that.

00:01:51.111 --> 00:01:52.195
And

00:01:52.195 --> 00:01:53.571
now Claude will run off

00:01:53.571 --> 00:01:54.572
in this loop

00:01:54.572 --> 00:01:55.907
with Playwright

00:01:55.907 --> 00:01:58.618
and continue making changes,

00:01:58.618 --> 00:01:59.911
validating them,

00:01:59.911 --> 00:02:01.830
and iterating on that.

00:02:01.830 --> 00:02:02.455
There we go.

00:02:02.455 --> 00:02:03.164
We have the summary

00:02:03.164 --> 00:02:03.790
of all the changes

00:02:03.790 --> 00:02:04.499
Claude Code made,

00:02:04.499 --> 00:02:05.792
and it is ready

00:02:05.792 --> 00:02:07.377
for me to review the code.

00:02:07.377 --> 00:02:08.419
I still get to do what I love.

00:02:08.419 --> 00:02:09.212
I still get to write code.

00:02:09.212 --> 00:02:10.588
I still get to build things.

00:02:10.588 --> 00:02:11.798
I can focus on

00:02:11.798 --> 00:02:12.674
writing code from scratch

00:02:12.674 --> 00:02:13.424
if I wanted to,

00:02:13.424 --> 00:02:14.884
but now I can think about, like,

00:02:14.884 --> 00:02:15.260
hey,

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:16.469
how does the broader system

00:02:16.469 --> 00:02:17.262
come together?

00:02:17.262 --> 00:02:19.013
And now I can focus more on

00:02:19.013 --> 00:02:20.515
the higher level decisions

00:02:20.515 --> 00:02:21.349
related to that.

00:02:21.349 --> 00:02:21.975
So it’s like, ok

00:02:21.975 --> 00:02:22.934
you’ve given me the data I need,

00:02:22.934 --> 00:02:24.102
now I can think about the strategy,

00:02:24.102 --> 00:02:24.936
I can think about

00:02:24.936 --> 00:02:25.645
what trade-offs

00:02:25.645 --> 00:02:26.187
we need to make

00:02:26.187 --> 00:02:27.147
with this information.

00:02:27.147 --> 00:02:27.939
I can think about

00:02:27.939 --> 00:02:28.648
how this fits in

00:02:28.648 --> 00:02:29.315
with other teams

00:02:29.315 --> 00:02:30.775
and then figure out

00:02:30.775 --> 00:02:32.318
the more human aspects

00:02:32.318 --> 00:02:33.027
of the work

00:02:33.027 --> 00:02:34.279
we need to get done.

00:02:34.821 --> 00:02:36.364
I mean, it’s absolutely ridiculous.

00:02:36.364 --> 00:02:37.073
It really is.

00:02:37.073 --> 00:02:39.993
It’s kind of mind-blowing.

00:02:39.993 --> 00:02:42.787
Claude Code has helped me

00:02:42.787 --> 00:02:43.955
dream bigger.

00:02:43.955 --> 00:02:45.206
I felt like I was always

00:02:45.206 --> 00:02:47.417
limited by what

00:02:47.417 --> 00:02:49.460
languages I’m proficient at.

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:51.337
It’s just opened up

00:02:51.337 --> 00:02:52.338
a whole lot of possibilities

00:02:52.338 --> 00:02:53.214
of things you can get done.

